    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>When you request serialization for a type from a Gson instance, it checks if it already has a TypeAdapter instance for that type, and if so it re-uses it (however note that AFAICT this is not an API contract, it is an internal optimization). If no adapter is available, it will try all registered TypeAdapter factories until one produces a TypeAdapter rather than null, and then it will cache the result.</p>\n<p>One of the built in TypeAdapter factories is ReflectiveTypeAdapterFactory. This factory does reflection over the fields of the object once at construction time then stores field mapping information in a <a href=\"https://github.com/google/gson/blob/72537db9a6095720aca3a67abe77ec5a16200081/gson/src/main/java/com/google/gson/internal/bind/ReflectiveTypeAdapterFactory.java#L292\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><code>FieldsData</code></a> object. It then uses this for serialization/deserialization.</p>\n<p>So yes, Gson does cache some refletion information, however it still is making reflected calls to actually get or set fields and my be doing runtime access checks. So this caching only prevents it from needing to re-scan the type definition to find the field names and annotations, which is still probably pretty helpful for performance, since they're able to e.g. store a <code>Map</code> from Json field names to the object fields that should be filled by that name.</p>\n"
  } ],
